'''Shlomo Moran''' ({{lang-he|שלמה מורן}}; born 1947) is an [[Israelis|Israeli]] [[computer scientist]], the Bernard Elkin Chair in Computer Science at the [[Technion – Israel Institute of Technology]] in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]].<ref>[http://www.cs.technion.ac.il/people/moran/ Faculty profile], the Technion, retrieved 2010-12-02.</ref>
Moran received his Ph.D. in 1979 from the Technion, under the supervision of [[Azaria Paz]]; his dissertation was entitled "NP Optimization Problems and their Approximation".<ref>{{mathgenealogy|name=Shlomo Moran|id=42276}}.</ref>
Several PhD students of Moran joined the academia as well, including [[Shlomi Dolev]], [[Ilan Gronau]], [[Shay Kutten]], and [[Gadi Taubenfeld]].
In 1993 he shared the [[Gödel Prize]] with [[László Babai]], [[Shafi Goldwasser]], [[Silvio Micali]], and [[Charles Rackoff]] for their work on [[Arthur–Merlin protocol]]s and [[interactive proof system]]s.<ref>[http://www.sigact.org/Prizes/godel/1993.html 1993 Gödel Prize] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208062326/http://www.sigact.org/Prizes/Godel/1993.html |date=2015-12-08 }}, [[Association for Computing Machinery|ACM]] [[SIGACT]], retrieved 2010-12-02.</ref>
